The basic idea of a =E2=80=9Cblack swan fund=E2=80=9D is that you have $100=
 invested in normal assets somewhere else, and you pay the black swan fund =
like $1 a year for insurance. In a normal year, your normal assets go up 15=
% or whatever and you make $15, and your black-swan premium is just an expe=
nse; you lose the dollar, for a net return of 14%. And in a catastrophic ye=
ar, your normal assets go down 20% or whatever and you lose $20, but your b=
lack-swan insurance pays out and you get back $20, for a net return of 0%, =
which is pretty good.
What is the performance of the black swan fund in the normal year? Well, ne=
gative 100%, give or take. (These are stylized schematic numbers, don=E2=80=
=99t take them too seriously.) But the black-swan manager doesn=E2=80=99t t=
hink of it that way, and you probably shouldn=E2=80=99t either. Instead the=
 argument is something like: =E2=80=9CIf you didn=E2=80=99t have this black=
-swan insurance, you=E2=80=99d have to invest much more conservatively, kee=
p more assets in cash, etc., so your return on your $100 of normal assets w=
ould only be like 8%. But the insurance gives you the confidence to invest =
more aggressively, so you made 15% on your normal assets, though you paid 1=
% for that insurance. So really the black swan fund added 6% to your overal=
l return.=E2=80=9D
Fine. What is the performance of the black swan fund in the catastrophic ye=
ar? Oh ha it is absolutely +1,900%, come on, it made $19 on $1 of premium. =
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Justina Lee reported last week on   the returns at Mark=
 Spitznagel=E2=80=99s Universa Investments:

Sure, all hedge funds like to put a positive spin on performance, and that=
=E2=80=99s well understood by their sophisticated clientele. But critics li=
ke Saba Capital Management founder Boaz Weinstein and Citadel=E2=80=99s for=
mer global head of fixed income, Derek Kaufman, say Miami-based Universa go=
es a step too far, cherry-picking data to burnish results. ...
The latest spat broke out on Twitter in the wake of Spitznagel=E2=80=99s Ja=
nuary missive to clients. As he touted the virtues of Universa=E2=80=99s st=
yle of hedging, he claimed a small allocation to the money manager equated =
to an =E2=80=9Cannuity paying 114% a year.=E2=80=9D
Considering that when Covid hit in March 2020, the firm said it returned 3,=
612% in a single month, that didn=E2=80=99t seem like much. But it appears =
to have been a final straw for naysayers such as Weinstein and Kaufman.
=E2=80=9CNone of what they are saying makes sense,=E2=80=9D tweeted Kaufman=
, while Weinstein =E2=80=94 who runs his own tail-hedge strategy in the cre=
dit realm =E2=80=94 called the firm out for the way it calculates its figur=
es. =E2=80=9CName another hedge fund or tail hedge fund that talks in retur=
ns on premia spent over some interval instead of return on assets,=E2=80=9D=
 he tweeted. ...
=E2=80=9CWhile we cannot comment on returns, Universa Founder and CIO, Mark=
 Spitznagel=E2=80=99s recent book, Safe Haven, explains in detail that the =
point of what Universa does is raise a portfolio=E2=80=99s rate of returns =
as a direct consequence of lowering its systematic risk,=E2=80=9D Brandon Y=
arckin, chief operating officer at Universa, wrote in an email. =E2=80=9CCo=
ntrary to Modern Portfolio Theory, this is the metric that matters, and it =
is demonstrably what we have done in Universa=E2=80=99s 15 year life to dat=
e.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
What Universa in effect does is calculate the return on an insurance policy=
 using only one month of premium. Conveniently ignored there is the reality=
 that clients typically pay Universa for protection for years =E2=80=94 a p=
rocess so painful it=E2=80=99s known as the =E2=80=9Cbleed=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94 before ever cashing in. =E2=80=A6
To compound the confusion, Universa=E2=80=99s AUM =E2=80=94 now $16.4 billi=
on =E2=80=94 is actually defined in a regulatory filing as the =E2=80=9Camo=
unt of equity market risk that a client seeks to protect.=E2=80=9D That mea=
ns the assets at the firm=E2=80=99s disposal are in practice far smaller.=
=C2=A0

Universa=E2=80=99s clients have $16.4 billion of assets (somewhere else) th=
at they protect by paying premium to Universa, and =E2=80=9Cwhat Universa d=
oes,=E2=80=9D in the long term,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cis raise [that $16.4 billion]=
=C2=A0portfolio=E2=80=99s rate of returns as a direct consequence of loweri=
ng its systematic risk.=E2=80=9D But what Universa does in any particularly=
 disastrous month for the stock market is earn a 3,612% return on=C2=A0that=
 month=E2=80=99s premium. Most of the time Universa leads with the first th=
ing =E2=80=94=C2=A0lowering systemic risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in the months =
where it 36x=E2=80=99s its money it leads with that.

