<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One fun little financial story=C2=A0of 2017 an=
d 2018 involved the bonds of American Media Inc., the publisher of the Nati=
onal Enquirer.=C2=A0AMI was majority-owned by a hedge fund firm named=C2=A0=
Chatham Asset Management LLC. It had some bonds outstanding. Those bonds di=
d not trade much, but they traded some, and they kept trading at higher and=
 higher prices. By November 2017, some AMI bonds were trading at lower yiel=
ds than the bonds of Apple Inc.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0I am sure AMI is a fine tabloid publisher but it is not Apple, an=
d its bond prices were perplexing. Also in 2018 AMI tried to raise some mor=
e money <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31118652.2=
57452/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZm9yYmVzLmNvbS9zaXRlcy9kZWJ0d2lyZS8yMDE4LzA3LzI3L2FtZ=
XJpY2FuLW1lZGlhLXF1aWV0bHktc2Vla2luZy00MjUtbWlsbGlvbi1pbi1ib25kcy1hcy1sZWdh=
bC1hbmQtcG9saXRpY2FsLXNwZWN0YWNsZS1zd2lybHMvP3NoPTY0ZTAyYjk3MjU2Mw/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB077398bd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> by selling more bonds</a>, and it event=
ually sold them at a 10.5% interest rate, which was much higher than the tr=
ading yield of its existing bonds. To the naked eye,=C2=A0AMI looked like a=
 small, high-yield newspaper publisher, and when it sold new bonds the pric=
es reflected that. But its=C2=A0<em>old=C2=A0</em>bonds traded in the secon=
dary market at prices that made it look more creditworthy than Apple. What =
gives?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everyone kind of knew the answer, which is tha=
t the AMI bonds didn=E2=80=99t trade that much, and they seemed to trade mo=
stly <em>within Chatham</em>:<br />Chatham, the majority equity owner of AM=
I=E2=80=99s stock, also owned most of its bonds, and sometimes Chatham woul=
d sell the bonds to itself at ever-increasing prices. This didn=E2=80=99t c=
ost Chatham much =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was basically just overpaying itself =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and made AMI=E2=80=99s credit look good. But of course when AMI=
 wanted to raise money by selling more bonds, Chatham was not going to buy =
those bonds at a 2% interest rate; it wanted a regular interest rate, like =
10.5%.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not particularly legal, and last week =
Chatham and its founder Anthony Melchiorre=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31118652.257452/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMDMvY2hhdGhhbS1mb3VuZGVyLXRvLXBheS0xOS1t=
aWxsaW9uLW92ZXItc2VjLWNhc2Utb24tYm9uZC10cmFkZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxMDIzX01PTkV=
ZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09Mj=
MwNDEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa1513ce5" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">settled with the US Securities and Exchange Commission</a>, agreeing=
 to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31118652.25745=
2/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy03Mg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB55090d03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pay $19 million</a> for doing this. <em>W=
hy=C2=A0</em>did Chatham do this? The story that <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31118652.257452/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9s=
aXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvaWEtNjI3MC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB48ece1=
66" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> the SEC tells</a> is basically that Chatham liked the bonds a=
 lot and didn=E2=80=99t want to let them go. Chatham ran a bunch of differe=
nt accounts =E2=80=94=C2=A0some hedge funds, some liquid alternatives funds=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and held large AMI bond positions=C2=A0in all of them. Some=
times some accounts would need to sell AMI bonds: They had concentration li=
mits that meant they couldn=E2=80=99t have too much of their money in AMI b=
onds, or customers took money out and Chatham needed to sell bonds to pay t=
hem. When this happened, Chatham did not want to let the bonds go, so it so=
ld them to other Chatham=C2=A0accounts so they could stay in the family. <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31118652.257452/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvaWEtNjI3MC5wZGY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cC48ece166" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The SEC says</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Generally, when Chatham was forced=
 to sell a high conviction AMI Bond in these circumstances, Chatham desired=
 to purchase the AMI Bond for another Client because Chatham still believed=
 in the merits of the investment and would not otherwise be selling the AMI=
 Bonds if it were not for the portfolio restrictions or cash needs of the s=
elling Clients.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a general matter, selling bonds to yourself=
=C2=A0is allowed, but awkward: If you really believe in some bonds but have=
 to sell them from one account, and you want to buy them in another account=
, you are not=C2=A0<em>forbidden=C2=A0</em>from doing so, but there are lot=
s of ways for it to look bad. Generally the ways for it to look bad are (1)=
 you overpay for the bonds, making money for the selling account at the exp=
ense of the buying account (and causing the reported trading price of the b=
onds to be wrong) or=C2=A0(2) you underpay for the bonds, making money for =
the buying=C2=A0account at the expense of the selling account=C2=A0(and cau=
sing the reported trading price of the bonds to be wrong). The solution is =
generally to sell yourself the bonds at a=C2=A0fair market price, neither u=
nderpaying nor overpaying. Broadly speaking two ways to do that are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell the bonds into the market at mar=
ket prices, and then buy them back a bit later from the market at market pr=
ices: You don=E2=80=99t trade with yourself at all, but only with arm=E2=80=
=99s-length counterparties; or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Fig=
ure out a fair market price using outside sources (trading pries, pricing s=
ervices, quotes from dealers, etc.) and sell the bonds to yourself at that =
price.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first option is probably better, but it re=
quires an active market; if you=E2=80=99re the only real buyer or seller of=
 the bonds it=E2=80=99s hard.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Chatham sort of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0waved in=
 the direction of doing this the right way?</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Recognizing that there were legal =
restrictions on trading between RICs<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and their affiliates, which included other Chatham Clients, Chath=
am and Melchiorre sought advice from a compliance consultant on how to faci=
litate the Rebalancing Trades. The consultant advised Chatham to conduct th=
e trading either through a single broker over more than one day or through =
multiple brokers if on the same day. The foundational principle underlying =
the advice was to ensure that the transactions occurred at independently-de=
rived market prices.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah I mean that=E2=80=99s good generic advice=
, but when you are the market for the bonds it doesn=E2=80=99t work out gre=
at. Also Chatham did not necessarily go all in on the=C2=A0<em>spirit=C2=A0=
</em>of that advice:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Around the time that Chatham began to execute =
the Rebalancing Trades, Melchiorre generally explained the purpose of the R=
ebalancing Trades to the Rebalancing Brokers. Melchiorre informed each of t=
he Rebalancing Brokers to whom he sold a Client=E2=80=99s AMI Bonds that he=
 likely would have an interest in repurchasing that same AMI Bond he was se=
lling for another Client. Over time, an understanding developed on the part=
 of the Rebalancing Brokers that whenever Melchiorre placed an order to sel=
l one of the AMI Bonds for a Client, he would repurchase it for another Cli=
ent, either directly the following day or days, or indirectly through anoth=
er broker.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Rebalancing Brokers engaged in the Rebalan=
cing Trades because they expected Melchiorre to repurchase the bonds. The b=
usiness model of several of the Rebalancing Brokers was to =E2=80=9Cmatch=
=E2=80=9D buy and sell orders from their customers. Those Rebalancing Broke=
rs ordinarily did not purchase securities for their own inventory=E2=80=94i=
.e., put the firm=E2=80=99s own capital at risk=E2=80=94or they did so on a=
 very limited basis. Nonetheless, the vast majority of the Rebalancing Trad=
es involved at least one Rebalancing Broker that purchased bonds into its f=
irm=E2=80=99s inventory. For example, some of the Rebalancing Brokers would=
 at times agree to purchase securities from Chatham even though the Rebalan=
cing Broker may not have lined up the other leg of the transaction. These b=
rokers=E2=80=99 willingness to do so was based on their expectation that Ch=
atham would repurchase the bonds, either directly or through another broker=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The purchasing Rebalancing Brokers generally d=
id not offer the AMI Bonds to other customers in the market. Instead, in vi=
rtually every case, they resold the securities to Chatham or to another bro=
ker who they understood was purchasing for Chatham.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Chatham=E2=80=99s need to conduct rebalanci=
ng in its various Client Accounts increased over time, Rebalancing Trades b=
ecame routine. When Melchiorre wanted to sell an AMI Bond to one particular=
 Rebalancing Broker (=E2=80=9CRebalancing Broker A=E2=80=9D) and then repur=
chase it the following day, he would send Rebalancing Broker A a message in=
dicating that he wanted to sell an AMI Bond in the =E2=80=9Cusual drill.=E2=
=80=9D Rebalancing Broker A then would purchase the AMI Bond into the firm=
=E2=80=99s inventory until Melchiorre repurchased it the following day.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the abstract, selling bonds to a broker one=
 day and then buying them back for a different account a day or two later c=
ould be a good way to do everything at arm=E2=80=99s-length market prices: =
The broker will pay, and charge, prices that reflect market levels; it won=
=E2=80=99t overpay to buy from you or undercharge to sell to you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in practice, if you are the only buyer and=
 the only seller and you call up a broker and say =E2=80=9Chey it=E2=80=99s=
 the usual drill,=E2=80=9D you are not really getting a fair market price. =
The broker doesn=E2=80=99t care what the buying price or selling price is, =
as long as you pay=C2=A0a commission. You can just pick whatever price you =
want:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Melchiorre proposed the price for the Rebalanc=
ing Trades and the Rebalancing Brokers agreed to it without first solicitin=
g bids from other market participants.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When proposing a price for Rebalancing Trades,=
 Melchiorre considered a number of factors, which included the prior day=E2=
=80=99s price as reflected in prices published by a pricing service. Those =
published prices would have been influenced, to some extent, by Chatham=E2=
=80=99s own trading. When purchasing the AMI Bonds, Melchiorre also added a=
 spread to compensate the Rebalancing Brokers. For example, in the case of =
a Rebalancing Trade executed through a single Rebalancing Broker overnight,=
 Chatham would repurchase the AMI Bonds for a small spread above what it ha=
d sold the AMI Bonds to the broker the day before.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One consequence of this is that the compliance=
 consultant=E2=80=99s basic idea of selling to brokers to get market prices=
 was not really working. Another consequence is that the prices kept going=
=C2=A0<em>up:=C2=A0</em>The only trades were Chatham=E2=80=99s trades, and =
it kept trading at=C2=A0higher prices to compensate its brokers. Eventually=
 this became absurd:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the Relevant Period, Chatham and Melchior=
re engaged in over one hundred Rebalancing Trades in AMI Bonds, accounting =
for approximately 81 percent, on average, of the customer trading (i.e., no=
t broker-to-broker trading) in such securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over time, the frequent Rebalancing Trades and=
 repeated mark-ups to compensate the Rebalancing Brokers resulted in the ma=
rket price of AMI Bonds increasing at a faster rate than prices of similar =
securities. For example, by November 2017, two of the AMI Bonds traded in R=
ebalancing Trades at implied yields lower than the prevailing London Interb=
ank Offered Rate (=E2=80=9CLIBOR=E2=80=9D). Such yields ordinarily would ha=
ve been associated with a bond of a much higher creditworthiness than the A=
MI Bonds.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third consequence is that Chatham=E2=80=99s =
assets under management kept going up: It charged clients fees based on the=
 value of its assets, and as it kept increasing the prices of these bonds, =
that value kept going up. The SEC says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chatham was compensated for its advisory servi=
ces to the [hedge] Funds with a management fee and a performance fee, and t=
o the [liquid alts funds]=C2=A0with a management fee. The management fee ch=
arged to certain Clients was set at a percentage of the [net asset value]=
=C2=A0of those Clients.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In order to calculate each Fund=E2=80=99s NAV,=
 Chatham used an independent pricing service to determine the value of each=
 of the portfolio securities, including the AMI Bonds. The LAF administrato=
rs calculated their own NAVs, also using the same pricing service Chatham u=
sed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chatham and Melchiorre understood that the pri=
cing service that Chatham and the LAF administrators utilized was based to =
some extent on recent trading prices and that the Rebalancing Trades accoun=
ted for virtually all of the trading in the Bonds during the Relevant Perio=
d. Because the Rebalancing Trades at times increased the prices of the AMI =
Bonds, the NAVs of the Client accounts also were increased by that amount o=
n those occasions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Accordingly, the Clients paid Chatham an estim=
ated $11,000,000 in performance and/or management fees that they would not =
have in the absence of Chatham=E2=80=99s Rebalancing Trades. Chatham in tur=
n paid approximately 55 percent of such fees to Melchiorre.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Part of the $19 million settlement is paying b=
ack that $11 million to investors. But the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t quite say th=
at this is=C2=A0<em>why </em>Chatham did this. You could argue that this so=
rt of thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0trading bonds back and forth with yourself in a =
way that raises their prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0is market manipulation, that th=
e goal was to raise prices to charge higher fees. But the SEC doesn=E2=80=
=99t say that: It says, more or less in so many words, that the reason for =
the trading is that Chatham really liked the bonds, that it =E2=80=9Cstill =
believed in the merits of the investment=E2=80=9D even when it had to sell =
them, so it kept buying them back. The higher prices and higher fees were j=
ust a happy byproduct.</p>
