<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic idea of a =E2=80=9Cblack swan fund=
=E2=80=9D is that you have $100 invested in normal assets <em>somewhere els=
e</em>, and you pay the black swan fund like $1 a year for insurance. In a =
normal year, your normal assets go up 15% or whatever and you make $15, and=
 your black-swan premium is just an expense; you lose the dollar, for a net=
 return of 14%. And in a catastrophic year, your normal assets go down 20% =
or whatever and you lose $20, but your black-swan insurance pays out and yo=
u get back $20, for a net return of 0%, which is pretty good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is the performance of the black swan fund=
 in the normal year? Well, negative 100%, give or take. (These are stylized=
 schematic numbers, don=E2=80=99t take them too seriously.) But the black-s=
wan manager doesn=E2=80=99t think of it that way, and you probably shouldn=
=E2=80=99t either. Instead the argument is something like: =E2=80=9CIf you =
didn=E2=80=99t have this black-swan insurance, you=E2=80=99d have to invest=
 much more conservatively, keep more assets in cash, etc., so your return o=
n your $100 of normal assets would only be like 8%. But the insurance gives=
 you the confidence to invest more aggressively, so you made 15% on your no=
rmal assets, though you paid 1% for that insurance. So really the black swa=
n fund added 6% to your overall return.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine. What is the performance of the black swa=
n fund in the catastrophic year? Oh ha it is absolutely +1,900%, come on, i=
t made $19 on $1 of premium. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Justina Lee reported last =
week on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31118652.2=
57452/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMDMvY=
mxhY2stc3dhbnMtYW5ncnktaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtYW5kLWhvdy10by1tYWtlLWEtMy02MTItcmV0=
dXJuP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJ=
jZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB01131766" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the returns at Mark Spitznagel=E2=
=80=99s Universa Investments</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure, all hedge funds like to put a positive s=
pin on performance, and that=E2=80=99s well understood by their sophisticat=
ed clientele. But critics like Saba Capital Management founder Boaz Weinste=
in and Citadel=E2=80=99s former global head of fixed income, Derek Kaufman,=
 say Miami-based Universa goes a step too far, cherry-picking data to burni=
sh results. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The latest spat broke out on Twitter in the wa=
ke of Spitznagel=E2=80=99s January missive to clients. As he touted the vir=
tues of Universa=E2=80=99s style of hedging, he claimed a small allocation =
to the money manager equated to an =E2=80=9Cannuity paying 114% a year.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Considering that when Covid hit in March 2020,=
 the firm said it returned 3,612% in a single month, that didn=E2=80=99t se=
em like much. But it appears to have been a final straw for naysayers such =
as Weinstein and Kaufman.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CNone of what they are saying makes se=
nse,=E2=80=9D tweeted Kaufman, while Weinstein =E2=80=94 who runs his own t=
ail-hedge strategy in the credit realm =E2=80=94 called the firm out for th=
e way it calculates its figures. =E2=80=9CName another hedge fund or tail h=
edge fund that talks in returns on premia spent over some interval instead =
of return on assets,=E2=80=9D he tweeted. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhile we cannot comment on returns, U=
niversa Founder and CIO, Mark Spitznagel=E2=80=99s recent book, <em>Safe Ha=
ven</em>, explains in detail that the point of what Universa does is raise =
a portfolio=E2=80=99s rate of returns as a direct consequence of lowering i=
ts systematic risk,=E2=80=9D Brandon Yarckin, chief operating officer at Un=
iversa, wrote in an email. =E2=80=9CContrary to Modern Portfolio Theory, th=
is is the metric that matters, and it is demonstrably what we have done in =
Universa=E2=80=99s 15 year life to date.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What Universa in effect does is calculate the =
return on an insurance policy using only one month of premium. Conveniently=
 ignored there is the reality that clients typically pay Universa for prote=
ction for years =E2=80=94 a process so painful it=E2=80=99s known as the =
=E2=80=9Cbleed=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 before ever cashing in. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To compound the confusion, Universa=E2=80=99s =
AUM =E2=80=94 now $16.4 billion =E2=80=94 is actually defined in a regulato=
ry filing as the =E2=80=9Camount of equity market risk that a client seeks =
to protect.=E2=80=9D That means the assets at the firm=E2=80=99s disposal a=
re in practice far smaller.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Universa=E2=80=99s clients have $16.4 billion =
of assets (somewhere else) that they protect by paying premium to Universa,=
 and =E2=80=9Cwhat Universa does,=E2=80=9D in the long term,=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=
is raise [that $16.4 billion]=C2=A0portfolio=E2=80=99s rate of returns as a=
 direct consequence of lowering its systematic risk.=E2=80=9D But what Univ=
ersa does in any particularly disastrous month for the stock market is earn=
 a 3,612% return on=C2=A0<em>that month=E2=80=99s premium</em>. Most of the=
 time Universa leads with the first thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0lowering systemic =
risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in the months where it 36x=E2=80=99s its money it l=
eads with that.</p>
